<br>

	<a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_family"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ed/Primary_Human_Language_Families_Map.png" height="150"></a></div>
	<br>

	<p>It is probably slightly difficult to ready, but the image above is of the language families in the world. The image (courtesy of <a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_family">WikiPedia.org</a>) gives a great overview of the different language families of modern language. You can also reach the Wiki page by clicking the map image. It'll open a new window though, but don't worry, my amazing website will still be open in another window for you to keep reading &#128519;. <br><br>

	If you are following the code until now, you'll notice that everything has been done in HTML and CSS. But soon, the real fun starts. Until then, let's give you some more insight into language families. <br><br>

	There are roughly 147 language families in the world. Within those families, roughly 7,000 languages are in existence. That being said, the definition about what constitutes as a language varies and some considered dialects can also be considered as mutually intelligible with another. <em>An infamous example of this would be the distinction between Bosnian, Croatian, and Serbian. Before the dissolution of Yugoslavian block, these three languages were considered as one. In a tragic post-war era, the countries that were once united have taken measures to separate themselves for political reasons.</em><br><br>

	Another unique example would be the case of mainland China. Colloquially, we often refer to Chinese as if it were 1 language that unites a people from China. Though that isn't entirely untrue if we are speaking in terms of the written language, there are nearly 300 different spoken languages in China by 56 different ethnic groups. In a country, with over a billion people there is a lot of linguistic diversity. China is a unique case though because 'Chinese' only has two variations of written form: simplified and traditional. So even if people on occassion cannot verbally communicate, they could in theory write to each other. Where there is a will there is a way. Right?

	</p>
